{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"36a28078-deb4-4638-b769-9073a328f218","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files matching your process name with a `.ips` extension (e.g., `MyApp-2026-05-01-014851.ips`).\n\n**Quick lookup:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if needed for lldb), enable them with:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file typically lands in `/cores/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1472157-6ebc-48af-8070-dd33c3c70e5f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search code or run commands. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":298,"requestId":"980D:24F9C3:BD6FB8:DDECB8:69F40683"},"id":"3c6018ed-446e-47ea-ae9d-c50f97371b06","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:58.829Z","parentId":"b1ebd311-5c1c-4185-95bb-9ea150675b51"}
